            "title": "Ali Toure \u003E \u200eR\u00c9PUBLIQUE-PATRIE-NATION (RPN)",
            "description": "#alpha8 #societe Societe : La CEI explique le cas de l\u2019\u00e9lecteur \u00ab n\u00e9 au 19 \u00e8me si\u00e8cle \u00bb Gagnoa, le 1er juin 2023 - La commissaire, superviseur des r\u00e9gions du G\u00f4h et du L\u00f4h Djiboua de la Commission \u00e9lectorale ind\u00e9pendante (CEI), Me Yapobi Ketty Yolande, a r\u00e9v\u00e9l\u00e9 mercredi 31 mai 2023 \u00e0 Gagnoa, que le... More#alpha8 #societe Society: The IEC explains the case of the voter \"born in the 19th century\" Gagnoa, June 1, 2023 - The Commissioner, Supervisor of the Goh and L\u00f4h Djiboua Regions of the Independent Electoral Commission (IEC), Me Yapobi Ketty Yolande, revealed on Wednesday, May 31, 2023 in Gagnoa that the case of the voter \u201cborn in the 19th century\u201d is a \u201csimple one.\u201d material error and not a case of fraud or attempted fraud\" in response to denunciations of frauds by the opposition recently in Abidjan. Me Yabobi indicated that this case concerns one of the areas of supervision of his competence, in this case Guitry in Loh-Djiboua, where in 2020, a similar case occurred. She explained that the CEI is accused of fraud, while elector Foussou Kouadio Krako, professor of his state, presented an Ivorian national identity card where he is mistakenly mentioned, born in 1871 instead of 1971. This voter appeared in 2020 at the rectification of the provisional electoral list, to have his date of birth rectified and the CEI decided to give priority to Foussou Kouadio Krako the right to vote, provided that he met all the conditions prescribed by the texts, stressed the IEC supervisor. According to Mr. Yapobi, IEC realised that it was a transcription error on its national identity card (CNI) that was not emanated from it. But since the IEC had no authority to correct this error, it was recorded as stated on its CNI, this date of birth in 1871, instead of 1971. \"To err is human and the provisional electoral roll is not free from error.\" That is why the dispute exists, which allows any elector to come and inform the IEC of an error that could have slipped on the list regarding this personal data,\" recalled the lawyer at the Abidjan bar. \"This is the reality of the facts,\" continued the deputy spokesman of the institution, who indicated that there could be other possible cases of such errors. She said that in the case, the IEC had benefited from the applicant's voluntary testimony, who explained it in 2020. On behalf of the Independent Electoral Commission, she recalled that errors could always be made on the list, and that the aim and mission of the IEC is to correct all of them, if not to correct as many as possible, with the help of the voters themselves. So Me Yapobi invited the people to come and check the electoral list and report any errors or irregularities that may have slipped there. The 2023 provisional list has 259,614 constituents in the Goh out of which 183,287 in Gagnoa ward, it shows. #prci #gouvci #rci #civ #LevraiSon #cicg #CEI  C\u00f4te d'IvoireTranslated from French",

MoreMinister Bouak\u00e9 Fofana, Minister of Hydraulic, Sanitation and Hygiene: The heavy rainfall on June 1st and 2nd has caused significant disruption to road traffic especially along VGE Boulevard to Akwaba roundabout. Today I undertook a series of tours including inspection at Akwaba Square located on Airport Road. Exceptional measures have already been put in place to optimize the flow of traffic, and we are seeing a gradual normalization of the situation. Several factors are at the cause of this incident, namely the decrease in the storage capacity of the toilet, as a result of the occupation and partial refilling carried out by the companies in charge of the PACOGA project (Grand Abidjan Port City Integration Project) and the Metro. In addition, the ongoing work on the Akwaba Square interchange has resulted to disruption in the drainage. On the other hand, it should be mentioned the obstruction of the drainage work and the outlet by the riverfront and industrialists. I have therefore issued instructions to the Director General of ONAD, Mr. Amara SANOGO, to convene an urgent meeting bringing together all stakeholders including MCLU, AGEROUTE, BNETD, PACOGA SIPF project, ONPC, Abidjan District and SICMA Abidjan Metro. Another sign of the end of American \ud83c\uddfa\ud83c\uddf2 economic hegemony? The Nilson Report reveals that Chinese payment cards UnionPay have surpassed US rival Visa for the first time. According to Sputnik, this is because of the increased Chinese exports to its neighbors and the fact that this system helps prepare for Western sanctions. Launched in 2002, UnionPay now encompasses 40.03% of the market, compared to 38.78% for Visa. Visa card transactions volume in 2022 was $14.109 billion, while UnionPay grossed 16.227 billion, a record for the Chinese system. The reasons for this record growth? First of all, let us recall that UnionPay has the monopoly of processing yuan transactions. Gold, an increasing number of neighboring countries use the Yuan to trade with China. In addition, UnionPay cards are helping several countries resist Western sanctions, even if they don't completely solve the problem of SWIFT disconnecting. UnionPay is now operating in more than 180 countries and the total number of UnionPay cards issued outside mainland China exceeds 200 million. MoreJEAN BONIN WILL BE \"PROUD\" OF HIS CITIZEN ORGANIZATION TO SETTLE PERSONAL AND POLITICAL ACCOUNTS The lawyer Jean Bonin Kouadio, once a leader of the Ivorian People's Front (FPI) and resigned of the said party for reasons of his own, is very close to Pascal Affi N'Guessan President of this party. Indeed, Jean Bonin, after leaving the FPI, created a Think Tank that is a citizen's circle of thought called FIER (Ivoirian Brotherhood for Understanding and Renaissance) of which he is the President. The objective or mission of this think circle is to expose bad governance including corruption in all socio-political and economic sectors. Through his critics as ingenious as acerbs, Ivorians continue to show him their admiration in this momentum of awakening consciences, and above all his willingness to serve as a lynx's eye in the prevarication generated by agents of public and private powers in the Republic. However, it is unfortunate that Mr. BONIN uses it to settle personal and political problems. It is strong to see that he used it to attack, vilify the candidate of the RHDP in the regional elections in MORONOU, the Honorable N'guessan Mathias AHONDJON deputy from Arrah, on the other hand Businessman, President of the company \"NEW ENTREPRISE\". The Honorable AHONDJON deputy of Arrah is a candidate for the regional elections of MORONOU. His respective opponents of this election are the President exiting the region, aka President of the FPI AFFI N'Guessan, the PDCI-RDA candidate Mrs. Veronique AKA, and the PPA-CI Ahoua Don MELLO, former Minister of Equipment and former BNETD Director General, aka BRICS Representative for West Africa . In this regard, the collective opinion is surprised by the unorthodox publication of the President of FIER in this election eve on behalf of his association to denounce the functioning of NEW ENTREPRISE whose boss is the opponent of his mentor. Isn't this edifying exit designed to dirty, vilify, weaken the RHDP candidate for the benefit of his mentor? The question deserves to be asked, because the moment chosen by Jean BONIN to publish his denunciation seems inappropriate. \"Our battle against corruption, alongside in particular the minister in charge of the fight against corruption but also with the High Authority for Good Governance, is not a political action but a citizen, encouraged by the President of the Republic himself.\" '' He declares. It's a must to note that BONIN is using FIERCE to solve personal and political problems. Mr. BONIN seems to bring to the attention of collective opinion that he has conducted investigations into NEW ENTREPRISE during which he discovered that this company uses dubious practices to obtain public contracts and fails to pay its taxes. In addition, he adds that he discovered that this company has secured the Toumodi-Oum\u00e9 road rehabilitation deal through the manager's accointance with a powerful network of accomplices in different Administrations. He is also wondering how a company that is known in the import and export of vehicles among them can become a powerful BTP company in such a short time, making billions in business? Therefore, he is drawing the attention of the Director General of Taxation and the Speaker of the National Assembly to use their regal power to look into the case of the boss of NEW ENTERPRISE which is on one hand in violation of taxes and on the other hand unconstitutional which states in its Article 11 of Ordinance No. 220-356 of April 8, 2020 revision of the Electoral Code that: \"(... ) are also incompatible with the mandate of a deputy, the functions of head of company, chairman of board of directors, managing director, deputy director or manager exercised in companies or firms whose activity is primarily the execution of work, provision of supplies or services on account of or under the control of the State, of a Collective or of a national public institution or of a foreign State\u201d. We say that this provision of the law affects more than one the elected officials of the Republic. Singularly indexing Hon. AHONDJON is an act of design. Literacy plays a crucial role in our lives in helping us fill the gaps and redefine our path. This is how it can happen. ACQUAINTING BASIC SKILLS: Literacy allows us to learn how to read, write and understand the information around us. It gives us the skills we need to access information and communicate effectively with others. EXPANDING OPPORTUNITIES: When we are literate, we have access to a wider array of opportunities. We can continue our education, seek better employment, and make informed decisions regarding our health, finances, and life in general. EMPOWERMENT: Literacy empowers us by giving ourselves the tools we need to take control of our lives. We no longer depend solely on others for information or to perform simple tasks. We become more independent and able to make decisions that suit us best. SELF-CONFIDENCE BUILT: Learning to read and write can have a significant impact on our confidence. By acquiring new skills and overcoming literacy challenges, we develop a stronger self-esteem. It gives us the courage to explore new possibilities and to pursue our goals with determination. SOCIAL TRANSFORMATION:. Literacy can also impact society as a whole. When more people are literate it promotes economic development, reduces inequality, and strengthens citizen participation. An literate society is better equipped to meet challenges and build a better future for all. So it is true that literacy gives us the opportunity to catch up and rewrite another story of our lives. MoreNEW PLATE PLATE \ud83c\udde8\ud83c\uddee New registration system \/ Ivory Coast has a unique identification card for vehicles and their owners Among the number of innovations proposed by the New Initial Vehicle Registration System (NSIIV), initiated by the Ivorian Government, the assignment of an ID is included. It is an alphanumeric composition arranged in the format of two (2) alphabetic letters followed by three (3) digits and ending with two (2) other alphabetic letters that constitute the unique identifier of road transport in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire. According to the Minister of Transport, Mr. Amadou Kon\u00e9, the new registration system that comes into force since Thursday, June 1, 2023 in Ivory Coast, is designed according to international standards. It is mainly aimed at securing automotive goods and contributes to internal security. Adding that this new device also aims to facilitate the ongoing integration of the various databases generated in the various administrations of the road transport sector. A great novelty that takes place in the framework of the digitization of Transport administration procedures in Ivory Coast. #Stopalincivismesurlaroute Ministry of Transport, Ivory CoastTranslated from French",

The Minister of Communication and Digital Economy gave the information during a press conference he co-hosted this Thursday, June 1, 2023, in Abidjan-Plateau, with his colleague from the Promotion of Youth, Professional Employment and Civic Service, Mamadou Tour\u00e9. Ministers Amadou Coulibaly and Mamadou Tour\u00e9 will lead on this occasion an important delegation consisting of the major players of the industry including 12 startups and 2 incubators. 'We're going to this tech show like conquerors (... ). We're going to sell our startups. We gone sell their techniques. We are going to show them that they are not alone and that there is a regulated legislative framework in place today to accompany and empower them,\" Amadou Coulibaly said. In this year 2023, declared year of the Youth, the Ivorian government, through this event, has the objectives of promoting Ivorian startups and the entrepreneurial and technological ecosystem of the country, to present the initiatives in favor of the accompaniment and development of digital startups. For example, Abidjan has a population of more than six million, the number of broods in public hospitals does not reach 50. \ud83d\udc49 The MOTHER KANGAROO method In C\u00f4te d'Ivoire, premature babies saved by the \"mother kangaroo\" method To make up for the lack of brooders in Abidjan, the Treichville CHU successfully experiments this technique inspired by the Australian animal The [mother kangaroo] method, inspired by the Australian animal and developed by paediatricians in Colombia in the late 1970s, to alleviate the lack of carcinogens and fight the transmission of neonatal infections. Infant is placed against mother's (more often father's) chest in a skin-to-skin setting, permanently or intermittently, to create ideal conditions of temperature, affection and rest. Everything the great premature needs to survive. \ud83d\udc49 This method is practiced in Treichville. And it works. Since the centre opened in March, 356 have been rescued out of 360 children in critical condition \ud83d\udc49 It's a \"blessing\" for the Ivory Coast, where neonatal mortality is a disaster.             "title": "Izra\u00ebl Kouam\u00e9 \u003E \u200eR\u00c9PUBLIQUE-PATRIE-NATION (RPN)",
            "description": "FAUT-IL ACHETER DES ACTIONS SOUS-VALORISEES POUR GAGNER EN BOURSE \u2753 Quand on commence \u00e0 investir en Bourse, la premi\u00e8re id\u00e9e qui nous vient en t\u00eate c\u2019est de trouver une action sous-valoris\u00e9e en vue de pouvoir r\u00e9aliser un gros coup. Tous les d\u00e9butants connaissent ce terme sous-valoris\u00e9 parce que... MoreDO YOU NEED TO BUY UNDERVALUED SHARES TO WIN THE STOCK MARKET\u2753 When we start investing in the stock market, the first idea that comes to mind is to find an undervalued stock in order to be able to make a big hit. All beginners know this undervalued term because many financial analysts use it. But let me tell you, using undervalue in any way is avoided. What you\u2019re ignoring, or, if you will, what financial analysts refuse to tell you is that every analyst has their beliefs. And it is based on his beliefs that he devises his strategy. Analysts' beliefs may be different that's why opinions and recommendations are different. So if you use a financial analyst's strategy and don't believe him, you'll never make it. What types of beliefs are these? It must be said that there are several types of beliefs, but I will only talk to you about two (2) major beliefs: (By the way, a belief is like a postulate. That is, something that is not demonstrated but accepted). \u2022 The first belief is the efficient market belief: this belief believes that the price of shares reflects the true value of those shares. Based on this principle, no action can be underestimated or overvalued. So high ups or downs are just exaggerations that do not last in time. It's as if a driver decides to drive at 100km\/h between ABIDJAN and YAMOUSSOUKRO, there may be times when the driver decides to brake a bit and so the speed of the car will temporarily go to 90 to 80km\/h. Also, in a descent, the speed can also drop to 110 or 120km\/h. So, up and down, there will be small moments of speeding that won't change the overall pace of 100km\/h. \u2022 The second belief we may have is the belief of the inefficient market: That is, the investor believes that stock prices on the stock market do not necessarily reflect the true values of the shares. So here, some stocks will be undervalued and others will be overvalued. You see this is a belief as opposed to the first belief we saw. This second belief is used by stock investors and also by traders. In conclusion, I would like to tell you that if you are a beginner, before asking an experienced analyst for advice, you have to start by asking his beliefs. This will give you a better understanding of the strategy he is going to explain. Also, undervaluation is not a panacea to make money in the stock market. It all depends on your beliefs. Thank you for reading this article \u2757 If you liked it, you can share and\/or comment.Translated from French",

            "description": "#CIV\ud83c\udde8\ud83c\uddee  #PORT_AUTONOME D'ABIDJAN \ud83c\udde8\ud83c\uddee   LE NOUVEAU TERMINAL C\u00c9R\u00c9ALIER  MIS EN EXPLOITATION  Apr\u00e8s l\u2019inauguration du deuxi\u00e8me terminal \u00e0 conteneurs, le 2 d\u00e9cembre 2022, par le Vice-Pr\u00e9sident de la R\u00e9publique, SEM. Ti\u00e9moko Meyliet KON\u00c9, a eu lieu le mardi 30 mai 2023, la c\u00e9r\u00e9monie de mise en... More#CIV\ud83c\udde8\ud83c\uddee  #AUTONOME_PORT OF ABIDJAN \ud83c\udde8\ud83c\uddee THE NEW CEREAL TERMINAL MIS IN EXPLOITATION After the inauguration of the second container terminal, on December 2, 2022, by the Vice President of the Republic, SEM. Ti\u00e9moko Meyliet KON\u00c9, on Tuesday, May 30, 2023, the ceremony for the commissioning of the infrastructure of the new grain terminal of the port of Abidjan, in the presence of the Minister of Transport, Mr. They don't have anything to do. This infrastructure, just as strategic as the previous works carried out, has once again boosted the competitiveness of the port of Abidjan. Launched on 16 January 2020, at a cost of F70 billion CFA, this new terminal will allow the port of Abidjan to power, among others, and deal with 13.5m Tirant d'Eau (against 9m TE before the project) and 70,000 others tonnes of capacity (from 35,000 formerly), to improve ship and cargo handling cadres, to provide maritime and port services to shippers as well as logistics performance of the port of Abidjan, to reduce waiting times for ships, to increase the attractiveness of the port of abidjan for shipowners and to contribute to reducing the cost of life. Built on an area of 9 hectares of land, 7 of which will be assigned to build warehouses and storage silos, the new grain terminal, which welcomed its first two ships on Thursday, April 27, 2023, has 1,010 m of dock linear. On the other hand, this terminal has a social impact with 400 direct jobs generated during infrastructure work and 300 direct jobs under operation. In his speech, the Director General of the Autonomous Port of Abidjan, Mr. Hien Yacouba SI\u00c9, indicated that the objective of this work, was to make the Port of Abidjan, a grain hub by the performance of the handling and storage capacity that this terminal would now offer, before indicating that the realization of the superstructures will be finalized through a public partnership and private. Proud of this achievement, the first PAA official expressed his gratitude to the President of the Republic, SEM. Alassane OUATTARA, whose vision for development is worth the port of Abidjan to have top-notch infrastructures today, but also in M. Amadou KON\u00c9, Minister of Transport, for his tireless support in the implementation of these major development projects. M. Hien SI\u00c9 on the other hand congratulated and thanked Japan, a country that funded the project, through the Japan Agency for International Cooperation (JICA), TOA Corporation, the Japanese project execution company, the Port Community of Abidjan, the PAA technical teams and all the staff. For the Minister of Transport, Mr. Amadou KON\u00c9, the creation of this work on the port platform of Abidjan, the first ever cereal terminal in the Gulf of Guinea, is a food security issue for Ivorian and those of the subregion, to the extent that cereals are basic necessities. M. Amadou KON\u00c9 took advantage of this forum to reiterate the Government's congratulations to the Chairman of the Board of Directors of PAA, Mr. M. Abdou TOUR\u00c9, to Director General, Mr. Hien SI\u00c9, to all the actors in the Abidjan port platform and to all the partners in the development of the Ivory Coast. In conclusion, the Transport Minister announced for the coming weeks the start of rehabilitation work on the Port Boulevard, a project funded to the amount of F40 billion by the Millennium Challenge Corporation (MCC). The Ambassador of Japan to C\u00f4te d'Ivoire, SEM IKKATAI Katsuya, whose country funded the construction of infrastructure work, was also present at the ceremony. During his speech, after stating that the completion of this work shows the solidarity, friendship and bilateral cooperation between his country and C\u00f4te d'Ivoire, he expressed the hope that the construction of this terminal will contribute to further intensifying relations Cooperation between Japan and the Ivory Coast, which it called the \"locomotive of the West African subregion\". Mr. TOA Corporation Project Manager, Mr. Kyota NORIZUKI, it expressed its gratitude to the port authority for the trust placed in TOA Corporation for the completion of the work. He welcomed the completion of the project despite the difficulties encountered, including the effects of the global health crisis, Covid-19, during the launch phase. Recall that since 2012, the Autonomous Port of Abidjan has undertaken significant modernization work of its port platform contained in the two successive National Development Plans (NDP) 2012-2015 and 2016-2020. Thus, the pier of the fishing terminal, the widening and deepening of the entrance pass of the Vridi canal, the filling of the VridI-Bi\u00e9try bay by the construction of 43 ha of industrial land, a rolling terminal, a second terminal at containers and today a new cereal terminal. These modern infrastructures that have come to life are the fruit of the dynamic economic growth that the Ivory Coast has experienced for a decade, driven by the vision and ambition of the Head of State, SEM. More55th CONFERENCE OF THE HOUSING NETWORK AND FRENCH SPEAKING IN SENEGAL: THE DIRECTOR GENERAL OF HOUSING PRESENTS HOUSING POLICY IN IVORY COAST On the initiative of the Habitat et Francophonie (RHF) Network, several actors in the real estate sector of French-speaking and French-speaking countries met from May 16 to 18, 2023, at King Fahd Palace in Dakar, Senegal, around the theme: \"Effectively respond to the needs of affordable housing and sustainable: success models and factors\u201d, to exchange, understanding and share their experiences on the issue of social housing in Member States. On this occasion Mr. Celestin Koalla , Director General of Housing and Living Framework, Representative Mr. Bruno Nabagn\u00e9 Kone, Minister of Construction, Housing and Urban Planning, said that strong demographic and urban growth in African cities is one of the main factors that constantly emphasizes the shortage of affordable housing. Hosting the second panel under the theme: \"Facing Demand Constraints\", the Director-General of Housing and Life Framework presented the locations of housing policy in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire, from independence to President Alassane Ouattara's accession to power, in 2011. Then, he presented the actions that have been undertaken and are being carried out, in order to effectively meet the demand for housing. At the end of his presentation, the Ivorian strategy put in place was appreciated by the participants, in particular the one concerning the land issue, the realization of the primary VRDs and the reform regarding the creation of the National Agency of Habitat. They, however, encouraged the Ivory Coast to integrate the training aspect into the operation of the said Agency. MoreMinister Bouak\u00e9 Fofana: \"Dear inhabitants of Yopougon, The government's consciousness is fully awake for the water shortage you are enduring these days. Several of you have told me about this issue via private messages. On behalf of the President of the Republic, SEM Alassane Ouattara, and the entire government, I want to assure you that this situation will soon be a distant memory. Accompanied by Minister Belmonde DOGO, I have personally visited the place where the problem is concentrated. This is the rupture of an 800mm water line in the Gesco district. This incident is the cause of the interruption of drinking water supply in some areas of the municipality of Yopougon. We have given clear instructions to SODECI and ONEP to quickly resolve this situation. Technicians are currently mobilized and working tirelessly. Drinking water supply will be restored in coming days. Please know that we understand the inconvenience caused by this shortage and we are working to resolve this issue as soon as possible. Your comfort and well-being are the priorities for the President of the Republic. Rest assured that we are staying aware of the situation and working to provide you with a quick and effective solution. \"Translated from French",

            "description": "Depuis des milliards d'ann\u00e9es, les volcans \u00e9mettent de grandes quantit\u00e9s de gaz dans l'atmosph\u00e8re. Au XXIe si\u00e8cle, qui des volcans ou des Hommes rejettent le plus de gaz carbonique ? Lors de leurs \u00e9ruptions notamment, les volcans \u00e9jectent toutes sortes de poussi\u00e8res et de gaz. Leur composition... MoreFor billions of years, volcanoes have been emitting large amounts of gas into the atmosphere. In the 21st century, which volcanoes or man emit the most carbon dioxide? During their eruptions, in particular, volcanoes emit all kinds of dust and gas. Their composition depends on the nature of magma from which they are derived. However, the three main gases emitted by volcanoes are water vapor, sulfur anhydride and... carbon dioxide. These shows happened all the time, sometimes with more intensity. They can have local impact, when concentrated in low atmosphere. But they can also influence the earth's climate. Especially when those gases are injected into the stratosphere, which is above 10 to 20 kilometers in elevation. It remains to be known whether greenhouse gas emissions such as CO2 have a greater weight than anthropic emissions.Translated from French",

A large number of residents from the different departments of the Moronou region attended the presentation of the future representatives of the \"Houphou\u00ebtistes\" movement for the regional and municipal elections of September 2, 2023. The presentation took place under the supervision of the Minister of Health and Public Hygiene, Mr Pierre N'gou DIMBA, the State Inspector General, Mr AHOUA Ndoli Th\u00e9ophile, elected officials, departmental secretaries, as well as many residents who attended the inauguration ceremony Candidates of the RHDP. \"Mr. N'guessan Ahondjon has been chosen by the RHDP to be a candidate for president of the Moronou Regional Council.
